  <!-- ──────── FAQ ──────── -->
  <section>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div
        style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) minmax(0, 2fr); gap: clamp(32px, 6vw, 96px);"
      >
        <div>
          <span class="kicker">FAQ</span>
          <h2 class="h-1" style="margin-top: 12px;">
            Reasonable questions<span class="dot">.</span>
          </h2>
          <p class="body" style="margin-top: 22px;">
            Not seeing yours? <a href="#" style="color: var(--nag-orange);"
              >Email me</a
            >.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq">
          <details open>
            <summary>Why didn't I get a notification?</summary>
            <p>
              Notifications fire only for habits scheduled at a specific time of
              day. A "daily" habit with no time attached is yours to check in on
              whenever — nag won't interrupt you. Add a time to turn it into a
              scheduled habit and the reminders kick in.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary
              >What if I have several things due at the same time?</summary
            >
            <p>
              You get one notification, not five. Nag consolidates anything
              scheduled for the same time slot into a single nudge, listing the
              habits in it. Tap to triage; check in or skip each one inline.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>What's the difference between skipped and missed?</summary>
            <p>
              A <strong>miss</strong> is a scheduled slot that went past without a
              check-in — you forgot, or didn't get to it. A
              <strong>skip</strong> is deliberate: you tapped skip, optionally jotted
              a reason ("travelling", "rest day"). Skips silence the rest of that
              slot's notifications and are tracked separately from misses, so your
              compliance reflects what you actually intended.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>Does the app icon show a badge?</summary>
            <p>
              Yes — on your home-screen app icon. The number is how many
              scheduled slots are currently due and unaddressed. Check in or
              skip them (long-press the tile, or open the app) and the badge
              clears. Notifications themselves don't carry the badge — that's a
              home-screen-only indicator.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>Where's the streak counter?</summary>
            <p>
              There isn't one. Streaks reward perfect runs and quietly punish
              the rest, which makes you quit the day after you slip. Nag tracks
              compliance over weeks and months instead — the real signal that a
              habit is sticking.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>Do I need an account?</summary>
            <p>
              No. Nag stores everything locally on your device. There's an
              optional iCloud backup. That's it. No login screen exists.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>Can I sync between devices?</summary>
            <p>
              Yes — via iCloud, out of the box. Sign in on your iPad and your
              habits are there.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>Is there an Android version?</summary>
            <p>
              Not currently, and no immediate plans. Nag is a one-person
              project; iOS is what I can do well right now.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>How much does it cost?</summary>
            <p>
              Nothing. Maybe a one-time "pay me if you want" tip in a later
              release. No subscriptions ever.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>Is it open source?</summary>
            <p>
              Not currently — but the data format is documented and you can
              export everything as JSON or CSV any time.
            </p>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

